(Intermediate) Quest 6 - Hedera Consensus Service & Mirror Nodes
Introduction
In this quest, we’ll be covering the last of the three Hedera network services - the Hedera Consensus Service! We’ll be seeing how we can use it to create topics and log messages on the Hedera network. We’ll also be covering how we can use the Mirror Node API to query for information on the Hedera network. 
For queries on this quest, join our Discord, head to the #hedera-helpdesk channel and look for this quest's post.
Learning Outcomes
By the end of this quest, you will be able to:
  • Describe the Hedera Consensus Service
  • Create a topic and log messages to it on the Hedera network
  • Use the Mirror Node API service to interact with the Hedera network

Quest Walkthrough
Step 1: Hedera Consensus Service
In Quest 1, we learnt that there are three Hedera network services - 1/ Hedera Smart Contract Service, 2/ Hedera Token Service and 3/ Hedera Consensus Service. In Quest 4, we dived into the Hedera Smart Contract Service. In Quest 5, we learnt how to mint fungible and non-fungible tokens using the Hedera Token Service. In this quest, we’ll be covering our final Hedera network service - the Hedera Consensus Service (HCS)!
HCS is a consensus-as-a-service platform for creating decentralized, auditable logs and timestamped events for Web2 and Web3 applications. Its main feature is to serve as a message broker or message queue (explained in next paragraph) - this allows for the submission of arbitrary data such as events, votes, locations inventory, and application state to be logged to the Hedera network. All messages sent are immutable, time-stamped, and fair-ordered, making the HCS a fast and cost-effective solution.

Message brokers, also known as message queues, are software that facilitates the exchange of messages between applications, systems, and services. They allow linked systems to communicate directly, even if they’re built using different programming languages or deployed on separate platforms. In short, the message queue as a middleman helps integrate applications and automate message transmission. To know more about message brokers, refer here.

The following are some key features of the HCS:
  1. Topic Management - Topics make it simple to organize transactions, so each application only receives the messages it needs
  2. Consensus Order - Messages are put into consensus order and given a timestamp by the Hedera network, with cryptographic proofs, so they are verifiable and secure
  3. Audit Log - The consensus service can be used to create a tamper-proof log of history, or an audit log. This can be ideal for compliance use cases, where proven point-in-time data is required
  4. Scalable Transactions - Hedera uses a highly efficient consensus mechanism. This allows higher speed and scalability of network transactions
  5. Low Fees - The efficiency, and extremely low energy usage of the consensus mechanism enable Hedera to provide low fees, that are fixed against USD, so you always know what transactions will cost you
  6. Historical Data - Creating immutable topics on Hedera, means you will have the ability to store long-term verifiable data on-chain for the life of your use case

require("dotenv").config(); const { Client } = require("@hashgraph/sdk"); async function createMessageQueue() {  const myAccountId = process.env.MY_ACCOUNT_ID;  const myPrivateKey = process.env.MY_PRIVATE_KEY;  if (myAccountId == null || myPrivateKey == null) {   throw new Error("account ID or Private key are missing");  }  const client = Client.forTestnet();  client.setOperator(myAccountId, myPrivateKey);  // Part 1 - Create topic  // Part 2 - Subscribe to topic  // Part 3 - Submit messages to topic  client.close() } createMessageQueue();

This starting code is similar to what we did for the previous few quests - grabbing our Hedera Developer Portal account details from our .env file and establishing a connection with the Hedera network.
Step 3: Part 1 - Creating a Topic
The first step in creating a message queue is creating a topic. A topic refers to a channel on the Hedera network that’s used to send and receive messages. We can create a topic with the TopicCreateTransaction() API. Copy the code below and paste it under Part 1 - Create topic in your script.
const createTopicTransactionId = await new TopicCreateTransaction().execute(client);  const createTopicReceipt = await createTopicTransactionId.getReceipt(client);  const newTopicId = createTopicReceipt.topicId;  console.log("The new topic ID is " + newTopicId);

You have the option of creating a public or private topic. A public topic is one that does not have a topic key meaning that anyone can submit messages to that topic. On the other hand, a private topic can be optionally set with a topic key .setASubmitKey(). The submitKey is required to sign the transaction for submitting messages to a private topic. Here, we’re creating a public topic.
 
Once the topic is created, we want to grab the topicId from the transaction receipt. The purpose of the topicId is to be used to identify a unique topic to submit messages to. The topic ID will look similar to an account ID, e.g. 0.0.49289194.

We’ll also need to import the TopicCreateTransaction module into our script - replace line 2 of your code with the code below.

const { Client, TopicCreateTransaction } = require("@hashgraph/sdk");

Let’s test out our script! Open up a terminal and navigate to stackup-hedera. Once there, run the command below in your terminal to run the code in message-queue.js.

node message-queue.js

If you’ve followed correctly up till now, your terminal should display a topic ID. Refer to the image in ‘Expected output’ if you require a reference.

Step 4: Part 2 - Subscribing to a Topic
Now that we’ve created a topic, we’ll need to subscribe to the topic via a Hedera mirror node. Subscribing to a topic allows us to receive the stream of messages that are submitted to it. The client that we configured for testnet in our project setup already establishes a connection to a Hedera testnet mirror node.
To subscribe to a topic, we use the TopicMessageQuery() API. We start out by building our subscription by setting the topicId of the topic we want to subscribe to and then call .subscribe, passing in the client info.

If we want to subscribe to a topic immediately after creation, we must ensure that the topicId is available on the mirror nodes. One common way to ensure it's available is to set a 5-second delay. To do this, we’ll be creating a helper function delay(); this is a simple function that pauses the script for a specified amount of time.

Copy the code below and paste it above the createMessageQueue() function. You can refer to ‘Working code’ if you’re unsure of where to place it. This is the function we’ll use to delay time.

function delay(time) {  return new Promise((resolve) => setTimeout(resolve, time)); }

Copy the copy below and paste it under Part 2 - Subscribe to topic. Similarly, feel free to refer to ‘Working code’ for a reference on where it should be placed. This is the code we’ll be using to subscribe to our topic.

await delay(5000);  new TopicMessageQuery()   .setTopicId(newTopicId)   .setStartTime(0)   .subscribe(client, null, (message) => {    let messageAsString = Buffer.from(message.contents, "utf8").toString();    console.log(`${message.consensusTimestamp.toDate()} Received: ${messageAsString}`);   });

Notice that we also specified the .setStartTime(0) property - the integer is a unix timestamp (in seconds) representing the time at which the subscription should begin. If the value given equates to a time in the past, the subscription will receive all messages that were created before the current time. If it is set to the current time or the future, the subscription will only receive messages that are sent after the specified time. 

Feel free to refer to the code in ‘Working code’ for a reference on how your script should look like at this point in time. The attentive learner will notice that there’s currently something missing in our script - but not to worry, we’ll address it in the next step.
Working code

Step 5: Part 3 - Submitting a Message to a Topic
Now let’s try submitting our first message to the topic! We’ll be using the TopicMessageSubmitTransaction() API for this. We’ll need to pass in the topic ID as well as the message we intend to submit. Copy the code below and paste it under Part 3 - Submit messages to topic.
const newHCSMessage = await new TopicMessageSubmitTransaction().setTopicId(newTopicId).setMessage("Hedera rocks!").execute(client);  const messageReceipt = await newHCSMessage.getReceipt(client);  console.log(messageReceipt);

Before we run our script, we’ll need to import the new modules we’ve used. We’re actually behind on the module imports by 2! If you managed to catch it in the previous step, we haven’t yet imported the TopicMessageQuery module. Let’s import it now along with TopicMessageSubmitTransaction. Replace line 2 of your script with the code below.

const { Client, TopicCreateTransaction, TopicMessageQuery, TopicMessageSubmitTransaction } = require("@hashgraph/sdk");

Now we’re ready to test out our script! Run the command below in your terminal.

node message-queue.js

If all goes well, you should get an output similar to the image below. Let’s break down the information in the message receipt!



The topicSequenceNumber object stores the ordered number of messages that have been submitted to the Hedera network in this topic. Since this is the first message submitted to this topic, it displays a value of 1. Another thing we’ll highlight is topicRunningHash - this is a tamper-proof running hash that verifies the integrity of the message submitted.
Step 6: Part 3 - Submitting Multiple Messages to a Topic
We’ve seen how we can submit a single message to a topic, but now let’s see how we can send messages from multiple accounts to the same topic. We’ll be creating 7 new accounts on the fly and using each account to submit a message to the topic. We’ve already covered the code for how to create and fund a new account before in Quest 3 so if you’re up for a challenge, you can try to code the scenario listed above yourself!
Here’s what we’ll need to do. Copy the code below and REPLACE the code under Part 3 Submit messages to topic. We’ll need to import the following modules as well - PrivateKey, AccountCreateTransaction and Hbar. You’ll also need to replace REPLACE-WITH-STACKUP-USERNAME with your StackUp username. Refer to the code in ‘Working code’ for a reference on how the finished product of message-queue.js should look like.

for (let i = 1; i <= 7; i++) {   const newAccountPrivateKey = PrivateKey.generateED25519();   const newAccountPublicKey = newAccountPrivateKey.publicKey;   const newAccount = await new AccountCreateTransaction()    .setKey(newAccountPublicKey)    .setInitialBalance(Hbar.fromTinybars(10000000000))    .execute(client);   const getReceipt = await newAccount.getReceipt(client);   const newAccountId = getReceipt.accountId;   const newClient = Client.forTestnet();   newClient.setOperator(newAccountId, newAccountPrivateKey);   await new TopicMessageSubmitTransaction()    .setTopicId(newTopicId)    .setMessage(`REPLACE-WITH-STACKUP-USERNAME has an account with account id ${newAccountId} that completed action no. ${i}`)    .execute(newClient);  }

So what does the code above do? There’s a for loop that iterates 7 times - within each iteration, we:
  1. Create a new account and fund it with some HBAR (recall that we need HBAR to pay for network fees when interacting with the Hedera network)
  2. Change the configuration of the client to the newly created account
  3. Submit a new message to the topic using the newly configured client

Let’s test out our script! Run the command below in your terminal. You should get an output similar to the image in ‘Expected output’. Note: if the image is too small, press on the image and it should open in a new tab.

node message-queue.js

We can also see the messages submitted to the topic on a block explorer like Hashscan! Search for the topic ID and you’ll be able to see all the messages sent. Click into any one of the messages and you’ll be able to see its detailed information such as the account that submitted the message, which block the message was submitted to, which sequence number the message is within the topic, etc.

And that’s it for the message queue portion of this quest! Keep your terminal open as we’ll be using it in one of our steps later on.

Step 7: Introduction to Mirror Node API
In the next portion of this quest, we’ll be learning how to use the Mirror Node API to query for information on the Hedera network. Although we already covered the concept of mirror nodes in Quest 2, let’s refresh our memory before proceeding!
Hedera mirror nodes are read-only nodes that provide access to verifiable data on the public ledger. Mirror nodes receive information from the consensus nodes, but the mirror nodes do not participate in consensus. 

Developers can communicate with mirror nodes through the Hedera mainnet, testnet and previewnet REST APIs. It’s important to note the three different base URLS provided depending on which network you are wanting to query data from. Each network has its own BaseURL that can be used to access its endpoint:

  • Mainnet BaseURL - https://mainnet-public.mirrornode.hedera.com/
  • Testnet BaseURL - https://testnet.mirrornode.hedera.com/
  • Previewnet BaseURL - https://previewnet.mirrornode.hedera.com/

There are infrastructure companies that provide paid versions of the mirror nodes for businesses to utlise and build decentralized applications. That being said, you, as the developer, have the option to run your own mirror node following the documentation provided here.
Step 8: Querying For Account Information
Now let’s try out an API for ourselves! We can conveniently do so using Swagger UI, a tool that allows developers to visualize and interact with APIs. Since Hedera has three networks, it maintains three different collections of Swagger UIs, one for each network. Let’s try querying for information on the mainnet! Open up the Swagger UI for mainnet here.


For a start, let’s try calling the endpoint /api/v1/accounts; this API returns a list of account entities in the Hedera network. Expand the card by pressing on it (refer to image above). Then, press on ‘Try it out’ so that we are enabled to edit the query parameters. 



Let’s empty all the query parameters to see what output we get (refer to image above). Once you’re done, press on ‘Execute’.

If you scroll down to see the Response body, you’ll see that the API returned us with every single account created on the Hedera mainnet thus far. Notice that the account ID for the first account returned is 0.0.1 (the account ID of the very first account created on Hedera mainnet)!

Well, this laundry list of accounts isn’t very helpful. Let’s try narrowing down our search by specifying some query parameters! Scroll up to the ‘Parameters’ section again. This time, let’s query for the accounts that have a balance of more than 1 trillion tinybars (or 10,000 HBAR)! To do this, input gt:1000000000 into the account.balance field and press on ‘Execute’.

If you scroll down to view the results, you’ll be able to see the accounts that currently have a balance of more than 1 trillion tinybars (or 10,000 HBAR)! Refer to the image in ‘Expected output’ for a reference. Note that because there are too many accounts to return, the response body only displays up to 20 responses.

Step 9: Querying for Topic Information
Now let’s try querying for something else - our own topic that’s created on the testnet! Since we’re changing network to the testnet instead, head to Swagger UI for testnet here. 


Find the /api/v1/topics/{topicId}/messages endpoint and press on it to expand the card (refer to image above). Then, press on ‘Try it out’. 



Paste in your topic ID from Step 6 and remove the options from all the other fields (refer to image above). After you’ve prepared the query parameters, press on ‘Execute’ to fire off the API.

If all goes well, you should be able to get a response similar to the image in ‘Expected output’. If you look at data returned in the Response body, you’ll see that we get the data of the 7 messages sent to the topic we created. 

If you inspect the “message” field of each message, you’ll see that the data looks cryptic; very different from our original message of “stackup-username has an account with account id ${newAccountId} that completed action no. ${i}”. This is because the messages returned are Base64 encoded. If you copy any one of the messages and decode using a Base64 decoder, you’ll be able to get our original message!

Step 10: Summary
As usual, let’s end off the quest with a summary of the points we’ve covered to consolidate our learning! In this quest, we covered the last of the three Hedera Network Services - the Hedera Consensus Service. We’ve seen how we can create a topic, subscribe and log messages to it. We also covered how we can use the Mirror Node API to conveniently query information from the Hedera networks. 
Here’s a quick summary of the points covered in this quest!
  • Hedera Consensus Service is a consensus-as-a-service platform for creating decentralized, auditable logs and timestamped events for Web2 and Web3 applications
  • Hedera Consensus Service provides the ability to create topics, subscribe to topics and submit messages. The submitted messages are immutable, time-stamped, and fair-ordered
  • The typical workflow for getting started on using the Hedera Consensus Service is topic creation -> topic subscription -> submit messages
  • The TopicCreateTransaction() API is used to create a topic
  • The TopicMessageQuery() API is used to subscribe to a topic
  • The TopicMessageSubmitTransaction() API is used to send messages to a topic
  • Hedera mirror nodes are read-only nodes that provide access to verifiable data on the public ledger. Mirror nodes receive information from the consensus nodes, but the mirror nodes do not participate in consensus (unlike consensus nodes)
